Title:
MemoryModule — Load a DLL from Memory (In-Memory PE/DLL Loader)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- MemoryModule is a C/C++ library that implements loading a Windows DLL directly from an in-memory buffer rather than from a file path.  
- It solves the limitation of `LoadLibrary`/`LoadLibraryEx`, which require the DLL to exist on disk, avoiding “write-to-temp-then-load” workarounds.  
- The project effectively reimplements key parts of the Windows PE loader: mapping sections, applying relocations, resolving imports, and calling the module entry point, exposing an API similar to `LoadLibrary` plus extended hooks.  
- It’s useful for red teams, pentesters, malware developers, and also defenders/researchers who need to understand or emulate reflective/in-memory loading behavior.  
- It’s interesting because it provides a well-known reference implementation for in-memory PE loading and is commonly used as a building block for fileless execution and custom loaders.

Technical Focus:
- PE (Portable Executable) parsing and manual mapping
- Import Address Table (IAT) resolution and dependency loading
- Base relocations and image rebasing
- Section mapping, memory protections, and loader-like initialization
- Custom alloc/free and API surface (`MemoryLoadLibraryEx`, `MemoryGetProcAddress`)

Use Cases:
- Build custom in-memory DLL loaders for payload staging without touching disk
- Implement reflective-loading style execution in implants or red team tooling
- Embed plugins/resources as raw DLL bytes inside an executable
- Research/detect manual-mapping behaviors by studying a canonical implementation
- Unit-test PE loading edge cases (exports, high addresses, malformed input)

Keywords:
MemoryModule, in-memory DLL loading, manual mapping, reflective loader, PE format, Portable Executable, LoadLibraryEx, MemoryLoadLibraryEx, MemoryGetProcAddress, IAT, import resolution, base relocations, section mapping, VirtualAlloc, VirtualProtect, DllMain, fileless execution, Windows loader internals, C/C++ loader library